Docker is a set of platform-as-a-service (PaaS) products that use OS-level virtualization to deliver software in packages called containers.
# Docker is a set of tools to deliver software in containers.
# Containers are packages of software

Virtualization is a technology that allows you to create multiple simulated environments or dedicated resources from a single, physical hardware system.

The Hypervisor
At the heart of virtualization is a thin layer of software called a Hypervisor (or Virtual Machine Monitor).
The physical machine is called the Host, and the virtual environments created inside it are called Guests (or Virtual Machines / VMs). 
The hypervisor acts like a traffic cop or resource manager. It sits between the physical hardware and the VMs, intercepting requests from the VMs 
and allocating a slice of the host's CPU, memory, storage, and networking resources to each guest so they don't interfere with one another.

Each VM includes a full operating system (OS) along with the necessary binaries and libraries, making them heavier and more resource-intensive.
Containers, on the other hand, share the host OS kernel and only package the application and its dependencies, resulting in a more lightweight and efficient solution.
