 * docker image pull hello-world # pull command downloads the images without running them
 
dockerfile contains the blueprint to create images, just like images are for containers, the only difference is that Dockerfile is written by the user and image by the machine

Container​
Containers contain the application and what is required to execute it (dependencies); they can be started, stopped, and interacted with. 
They are isolated environments on the host machine, capable of interacting with each other and with the host machine itself via defined methods (TCP/UDP).
* docker container ls -a #lists all available containers, without -a flag, it just lists the running containers
* docker ps -a #short hand 
*  docker container rm 3d # imagine container's ID is 3d4bab29dd67, using the first few characters of an ID
* docker container rm id1 id2 id3 #multiple argument
* docker run -d nginx #-d flags means run nginx in the background, without it, this will take up the entire terminal
* docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx #Starts Nginx in the background and makes it accessible at http://localhost:8080.
* docker run -it -d --name iwemida ubuntu sh -c ' while true; do date; sleep 3; done'
 # --name iwemida _ this overrides the feature that assigns random names and forces "iwemida"
 # ubuntu - this is the image ran to form a container, It's a lightweight, stripped-down version of the standard Ubuntu Linux OS
 # sh -c '...' _ By default, an Ubuntu container launches into a plain shell or does nothing and exits. This parameter tells Docker: 
   "Don't run the default command. Instead, open a standard Linux shell (sh) and execute the following string of commands (-c)."
 #'while true; do date; sleep 1; done' _This is a classic Linux infinite bash loop broken down into four parts:
    -while true; – Start a loop that runs forever because the condition "true" is always true.
    -do date; – Print the current system date and time to the standard output.
    -sleep 1; – Pause the script execution for exactly 1 second.
    done – Marks the end of the loop iteration, telling it to go back to the top and repeat.

 * docker run -d --rm -it --name iwemida ubuntu sh -c 'while true; do date; sleep 1; done'
 # --rm - Automatically deletes the container after it stops.
(Ctrl + P, then Ctrl + Q) - This safely detaches your terminal screen and drops you back onto your host machine's command line,
 leaving the container ticking away silently.
 
 TO INTERACT WITH IT
 * docker pause iwemida  & * docker unpause iwemida #this pauses and unpauses the container
 * docker start iwemida #this restarts stopped container - docker start cont1 cont2 ..
 * docker attach iwemida #reconnects your terminal to the container. either it was -d detached or you using another window
 * docker attach --no-stdin iwemida # connects but cuts out stdin(your keyboard) - usecase: for watching log file and muting yourself incase you accidentally press a button
 * docker logs  -f iwemida #-f flag means follow (LIVE), so new log lines keep appearing in real time # the code shows the logs of the container.

WORKING WITHIN A RUNNING CONTAINER
 * docker exec iwemida ls -la  #exec means: Run a new command inside an already running container.
   #ls -la : - l flag -> long format (instead of just names, it prints type, size, permission, etc.), -a flag -> all
 * docker exec -it iwemida bash #opens a bash terminal in the container
 *docker exec -it iwemida sh #sh is more universal 
 *docker exec iwemida ls -la /usr/share/nginx/html #list all files in a path (to check if a file is missing)
 *docker exec iwemida cat /var/log/read.log #cat a file in a path (read a log file or check configuration files)
 *docker exec iwemida ps auxf #checks running processes in a container #can be run -it iwemida bash new terminal _ ps auxf
 *docker exec iwemida df -h #check disk usage
 *docker exec iwemida env #See all environment variables the container is using
 *docker exec iwemida curl http://localhost #curl request from localhost (container itself) - use case: if there is a web server inside, it fetches the webpage
 *docker exec iwemida ping google.com #Creates a file inside the running container.
 *docker exec iwemida python script.py #if python is installed, it runs the script without ending the container
 * docker kill iwemida # This command forcefully stops the main process inside the running container, sends SIGKILL immediately (or another signal if specified)
 *docker stop iwemida #Sends SIGTERM, waits (default 10s), then SIGKILL if still running
   #SIGTERM is a request. The process gets a chance to: Save unsaved data, Close open files/connections cleanly, Notify other systems it's shutting down,
  Run any custom cleanup logic, even choose to ignore the signal and keep running (gives well-behaved apps to shut down cleanly), else SEGKILL:
   #SEGKILL is an order. It goes straight to the OS kernel and ends the process out of memory instantly. 
     -The process: Gets zero warning. Cannot run any cleanup code, Cannot catch or block it — this is by design, so a truly stuck/unresponsive process can always be terminated
        # *docker stop -t 30 xxx   # give it 30 seconds before force-killing
 *docker kill iwemida #Sends SIGKILL immediately (or another signal if specified)
 * docker rm iwemida # command deletes the container entirely. It removes the container's filesystem, its logs, its network settings, and its metadata from your Docker host.
  # rm can't remove a working container except force delete:
 * docker rm -f iwemida or docker rm --force iwemida
 FOR CONTEXT: *docker kill iwemida && docker rm iwemida is equivalent to *docker rm --force iwemida 
   # This is because when kill is run, it stops but keeps the container & can be restarted with: *docker start iwemida



